@sarbian

I have been watching the landings done by the Landing Guidance module. The landing prediction appears to change dramatically as the spacecraft is rotated as if the computation was using the control point of the spacecraft (which is normally at one end of the craft). Prior to entering the atmosphere, the landing prediction is generally within a couple of meters of the target. As the landing continues the predicted landing point gradually moves longer (i.e., Eastward if you are approaching from the West). At the point at which the spacecraft goes vertical for the final decent, the landing point appears to move approximately 100 meters (for a spacecraft that is approximately 2 meters long).

All of these observations appear to be consistent with the landing simulation being computed from one end of the spacecraft rather than from the center of mass. The landing predictions might be significantly more stable (and accurate) if the simulation made the computations using the location of the center of mass of the spacecraft.

I had a few question about the new "ÃŽâ€V include cosine losses" option, or the fact that the Delta-V windows now report negative number.

Both are related to this new option. First you need to add it to your Delta-V windows if it's not here already (it here by default for new config). Press the E of the window and search for "ÃŽâ€V include cosine losses" in the Thrust section, then add it.

This option change how the Thrust is displayed in the detaV stats. If an engine is not aligned with the ship it will show a lower thrust when the option is active. Here is an example.

First when the engine are aligned with the "up" of the rocket (I turned them since those are not aligned by default)

With a 45Ã‚Â° angle you have only cos(45Ã‚Â°) = 70.7% of the original thrust

With a 90Ã‚Â° angle you have 0% of the original thrust

And in reverse you get negative thrust

The option only change the Delta-V info. MJ always know that an angled engine provide less thrust.
